The hearth dataset

Let us load the stanford2 dataset which is available in the survival library. From the documentation: Survival of patients on the waiting list for the Stanford heart transplant program.

The survival times are stored in the time variable which is either complete (status = 1) or censored (status = 0).

Let \(\textbf{t} = (t_1,\dots,t_n)\) be the observed survival times and \(\textbf{d} = (d_1,\dots,d_n)\) be the corresponding binary vector of censorship statuses. We load in R this quantities as follows, together with the Kaplan-Meier survival function.

library(survival)
data(stanford2)
t <- stanford2$time
d <- stanford2$status

# Kaplan-Meier estimate
fit_KM <- survfit(Surv(t, d) ~ 1)
plot(fit_KM)

Weibull model and likelihood function

We are interested in fitting a Bayesian model for estimating the survival function and quantify the associated uncertainty. A common parametric model for survival data is the Weibull model, having the following density, hazard rate and survival function

\[ f(t \mid \alpha, \beta) = \frac{\alpha}{\beta}\left(\frac{t}{\beta}\right)^{\alpha - 1}\exp\left\{- \left(\frac{t}{\beta}\right)^{\alpha}\right\}, \quad h(t \mid \alpha, \beta) = \frac{\alpha}{\beta}\left(\frac{t}{\beta}\right)^{\alpha - 1}, \quad S(t \mid \alpha, \beta) = \exp\left\{- \left(\frac{t}{\beta}\right)^{\alpha}\right\}. \]

The likelihood for this a parametric survival model, under suitable censorship assumptions, is the following

\[ \mathscr{L}(\alpha, \beta; \textbf{t},\textbf{d}) \propto \prod_{i=1}^n h(t_i \mid \alpha, \beta)^{d_i} S(t_i \mid \alpha, \beta) = \prod_{i : d_i=1}f(t_i \mid \alpha, \beta) \prod_{i: d_i = 0}S(t_i \mid \alpha,\beta). \]

The implementation of the log-likelihood in R can be done as follows:

t1 <- t[d == 1] # Full data points
t0 <- t[d == 0] # Censored data points

Then, we specify the likelihood function in terms of t1and t0.

loglik <- function(t1, t0, alpha, beta) {
  full <- sum(dweibull(t1, alpha, beta, log = TRUE))
  censored <- sum(pweibull(t0, alpha, beta, log = TRUE, lower.tail = FALSE))
  full + censored
}

Prior specification

In the Bayesian framework, we need also to select prior distributions. Since the focus of the course is on computations we do not explore the sensitivity to the prior and we present a single reasonable choice. Note that both \(\alpha,\beta\) are strictly positive, therefore we choose

\[ \theta_1 = \log{\alpha} \sim \text{N}(0,100), \qquad \theta_2 = \log(\beta) \sim \text{N}(0,100). \]

Hence, in R we can define the log-prior and the log-posterior in terms of the transformed parameters \(\theta_1, \theta_2\) as follows

logprior <- function(theta) {
  sum(dnorm(theta, 0, sqrt(100), log = TRUE))
}

logpost <- function(t1, t0, theta) {
  loglik(t1, t0, exp(theta[1]), exp(theta[2])) + logprior(theta)
}

Metropolis-Hastings

We aim at obtainins (possibly correlated) samples from the posterior distribution

\[ f(\theta_1,\theta_2 \mid \textbf{t},\textbf{d}) \propto \mathscr{L}(\alpha, \beta; \textbf{t},\textbf{d})f(\theta_1)f(\theta_2), \] recalling that \(\theta_1 = \log{\alpha}\) and \(\theta_2 = \log{\beta}\). This can be done using a random walk Metropolis-Hastings algorithm.

The algorithm we described is implemented in R in the following.

# R represent the number of samples
# burn_in is the number discarded: in total we sample R + burn_in values
RMH <- function(R, burn_in, t, d) {
  out <- matrix(0, R, 2) # Initialize an empty matrix to store the values
  theta <- c(0, 0) # Initial values

  t1 <- t[d == 1] # Full data points
  t0 <- t[d == 0] # Censored data points

  for (r in 1:(burn_in + R)) {
    theta_new <- rnorm(2, mean = theta, sd = 0.25)
    alpha <- min(1, exp(logpost(t1, t0, theta_new) - logpost(t1, t0, theta)))
    if (runif(1) < alpha) {
      theta <- theta_new # Accept the value
    }
    # Store the values after the burn-in period
    if (r > burn_in) {
      out[r - burn_in, ] <- theta
    }
  }
  out
}

We can now run the algorithm. We choose R = 50000 and burn_in = 5000.

R <- 50000
burn_in <- 5000
library(tictoc)
set.seed(123)

tic()
fit_MCMC <- RMH(R, burn_in, t, d)
toc()
2.138 sec elapsed

Estimation of the survival curve

grid <- seq(0, 3700, length = 50)

S_mean <- numeric(length(grid))
S_upper <- numeric(length(grid))
S_lower <- numeric(length(grid))

for (i in 1:length(grid)) {
  S_mean[i] <- mean(pweibull(grid[i], shape = fit_MCMC[, 1], fit_MCMC[, 2], lower.tail = FALSE))
  S_lower[i] <- quantile(pweibull(grid[i], shape = fit_MCMC[, 1], fit_MCMC[, 2], lower.tail = FALSE), 0.025)
  S_upper[i] <- quantile(pweibull(grid[i], shape = fit_MCMC[, 1], fit_MCMC[, 2], lower.tail = FALSE), 0.975)
}
library(ggplot2)
data_plot <- data.frame(Time = grid, Mean = S_mean, Upper = S_upper, Lower = S_lower)
ggplot(data=data_plot, aes(x = Time, y = Mean, ymin = Lower, ymax = Upper)) + geom_line() + theme_bw() + ylab("Survival probability") + ylim(c(0,1)) + geom_ribbon(alpha=0.1)
